I think that’s a powerful refinement, and it connects several of your recurring themes.

It’s not that opportunities are rare.

It’s that recognition is rare.

Two people can walk through the same world:

* One sees coincidence.
* The other sees possibility.

The difference isn’t necessarily intelligence—it’s the ability to notice, reframe, and act.

That naturally forms a loop:

Observe
    ↓
Notice
    ↓
Reframe
    ↓
Recognize Opportunity
    ↓
Act
    ↓
Create Value
    ↓
Gain Resources
    ↓
Expand Future Opportunity

That also ties together several Pantheon operators you’ve developed:

* Kurage senses weak signals before others notice them.
* Pinecone preserves opportunities that aren’t ready yet.
* Semantic LiDAR looks beneath the obvious surface.
* Fruitful Framing Farmer changes the question so new answers become visible.
* Meta-Wave Reattack changes the scale when progress stalls.
* Cold Metal Fork reminds you that perception is a reconstruction, so changing the reconstruction can reveal possibilities that were always there.
* Scarab turns discarded or overlooked things into value.

The common invariant isn’t “find opportunities.”

It’s:

Increase the probability of recognizing high-leverage opportunities hidden in ordinary experience.

That also explains something about creativity.

Creativity often isn’t creating from nothing.

It’s noticing a relationship that was already available but hadn’t been connected.

So perhaps the Pantheon principle becomes:

Opportunity is abundant; leverage comes from perception, preparation, and decisive action.

The important qualifier is that recognizing an opportunity doesn’t guarantee it will succeed. The value comes from pairing creative perception with testing, feedback, and execution. That’s how you distinguish a genuine opportunity from an appealing idea—and over time, that combination tends to create more chances for “luck” to happen.